The Civil Rights Movement has issued a travel warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Promotion of Colored People (NAACP) has issued warnings for colored people traveling to Missouri based on state discriminatory principles and racist attacks.
"The NAACP Travel Recommendation for the State of Missouri, effective August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, visitors and residents of Missouri to pay increased attention when traveling across the state as a result of a series of controversial racially motivated incidents that are currently occurring throughout the state," the state said in a statement.
The NAACP said it took this step on the basis of current laws of the state of Missouri that make it difficult to defend racistly motivated acts in court, as well as as a result of the conduct of bodies active in criminal proceedings that disproportionately target minorities.
“There is a violation of civil rights.
People are stopped by the police just because of their skin color, they are attacked or killed," Rod Chapel, president of the NAACP, told the Kansas City Star.
“We have the largest number of complaints to date.”
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization for the U.S. state.
Among the incidents cited by the organization were racially motivated accusations against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in controversial circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gasoline while traveling across the state and was thrown into custody by police without charge of a crime.
The travel recommendation also draws attention to a recent statement by Missouri’s Supreme Public Prosecutor’s Office, which states that black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped by police.
"The purpose of the travel recommendation is to alert people and warn their families, friends and associates of what could happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
“People need to be prepared – they should carry money with them for possible bail payments or notify their relatives that they are going to travel to the state.”
According to the current FBI program, there were 100 cases of hateful behavior reported in Missouri in 2015, making the state the 16th-highest among all states.
A travel warning is also a response to the new Missouri law, which makes it difficult to sue a company for discrimination in providing accommodation or employment.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) has issued travel recommendations for Texas and Arizona after states passed an immigration law that allows state officials to detain people based on violations of this law, which the ACLU says is intended to improve racial profiling.
Travel recommendations are usually issued by the State Department for foreign countries, but lately advocacy groups have resorted to these measures in response to specific laws and trends within the US.
