Poverty and Death in the Land of Gold
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she doesn't use a stove.
In fact, he rarely uses a pelvis.
In her wooden hut, located in the capital of Paniai Enarotali in the Indonesian province of Papua, a woman usually simply throws a sweet potato - in the language of the local "note" - directly into the fire.
After half an hour, remove the potato and taste it with unwashed hands.
Bardina sits on muddy ground - the house is not equipped with furniture - where she also performs her daily work, such as washing laundry in cloudy water from a nearby swamp.
A bucket in a room without a roof fills the toilet.
As the youngest of the four wives of her husband, she was not assigned any field for cultivation.
Polygamy is common here.
Working until late at night is a danger: most of the men in the village are unemployed and often drink alcohol. In addition, soldiers live in the village.
"In the afternoon after five o'clock, no one will be allowed to wander around the village," says Bardina.
It is a rare glimpse into daily life on the Papua, a former Dutch colony that was declared part of Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum in which only 1,026 elders were forced to vote by a public hand-raising in front of the occupying army.
The current anti-Dutch protest movement quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which controlled the entire region with the exception of foreign journalists or civil rights watchdogs.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua - independent Papua New Guinea occupied the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is such a remote and desolate city that you can get to after a ninety-minute flight from the capital of Jayapura province to Nabira, and then a five-hour gastric constriction ride.
Public transport in this area does not work.
The city with 19,000 inhabitants consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, roofs of woolen sheets in shades of gray and rusty color.
Very few Indonesians, indeed journalists, and practically no foreigners, looked at this place.
Before the arrival of the Christians, the locals worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
And that's not all.
“We weren’t used to wearing these dresses,” says Bardina, pointing to his colorful, hand-knitted turban, dark T-shirt, and shiny skirt.
"We used to only carry leaves."
Papua is the poorest province of Indonesia - 28% of the population lives below the poverty line and the child mortality and literacy rate is one of the worst in all of Asia.
At the same time, however, it is the country of gold in Indonesia.
The largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran of the American Phoeenix, is located just 60 miles from Paniai – a rocky province roughly the size of New Jersey, which is home to about 153,000 residents.
In 2015, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua supports wood mining in an estimated value of $78 billion.
These riches, however, are a source of suffering for the Papuans and a guarantee of oppression by the powerful Indonesian army.
An investigation conducted in 2005 by the New York Times found that Freeport paid local military officials and units about $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including $150,000 for one officer.
The Papuans calling for self-government threaten this golden goose and are therefore severely oppressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969 and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian army.
Mass murders in the Papuan tribal area during the 1970s amounted to genocide, the Asian Commission on Human Rights said.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
We Will Lose Everything, a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, describes the atrocities that took place last year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture – according to another report, rape and electric current execution are particularly popular – and the brutal suppression of peaceful protesters.
“It’s difficult to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week,” said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The whole situation was aggravated by the fact that Papuan sources were attracting settlers to Indonesia.
Of the province's 3.5 million inhabitants, 83% profess Christianity, but the demographics change with the influx of Muslim immigrants from the Indonesian islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javan canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado or a mixture of vegetables with peanut sauce.
The locals are fighting for survival.
“Immigrants have started selling chicken and vegetables in traditional markets at lower prices than local Papuans,” explains 24-year-old Abeth You, who was born in Paniai and moved to work in the capital of Jayapura province.
"The original inhabitants of Papua - mama-mama (women) - lost their jobs."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, nicknamed Jokowi, pledged to address inequality and rights violations during his 2014 presidential campaign.
The former carpenter secured his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta in 27 of the 29 districts of Papua, including Paniai.
But very little has changed in Papua and the local people feel betrayed.
“Our hearts were broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokpwi in the hope that he would hear our call for justice,” You said.
The fact is that just two months after Jakowi’s October inauguration, Paniaia experienced a major shock.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children sang a Christmas song at a campfire in the city of Enarotali, when two Indonesian soldiers on motorcycles emerged from the heat of the night.
Two of the surprised children told them they should turn on the lights.
One of the soldiers was touched by the sigh and tone with which it was pronounced and later returned with four other soldiers, local priest Yavedt Tebai said.
Two of the soldiers in the drunken state chased a group of children and beat them with their guns, reported victims and witnesses events.
One of the soldiers then fired at a group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so hard that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to the nearby Electoral Commission building, and the next day things were getting worse.
About 1,000 young Papuan men and women gathered on the football field in front of the local police station and military headquarters and demanded justice.
They came with ceremonial hunting bows and performed a wait dance - in which a circle is run and the singing of birds is imitated - the Papuan tribe Mee Pago.
Several Protestants began to throw stones at the buildings.
With increasing tension, the soldiers were given an order via radio: “If the crowd tries at least three times to resist, you are allowed to shoot,” according to the weekly TIME in an official document, the content of which was never published in the local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of the Enarotali district of Kego Koto, recognized the dangers and urged residents to move to their homes.
But no one paid attention to his words.
"When I turned around, someone shot me in the left wrist," he told TIME magazine on the porch of his colorful painted wooden house.
Kayame does not yet know who the shooter was, but according to him, the bullet belonged to one of the soldiers present.
“There were a lot of people around and a lot of shooting,” he added.
One of the locals, Alfius Youw, was shot three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
"I ran to the body to make sure it was really him," Yohanes, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, told TIME in a dismayed voice.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
A Papuan police inspector, General Yotje Mende, told reporters that his officers had only “secured” the station under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten us with death,” said Papuan police spokesman Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo in 2015.
“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five protesters were killed and many were injured.
The report of the murders was leaked to the Jakarta media the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi delivered a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing his understanding of the families of the victims and vowing to address the violence in Papua.
"I demand an immediate solution to this problem so that it can never be repeated," he said.
National Security Minister Wiranto announced in October 2016 that he would introduce an out-of-court mechanism to resolve violent acts that occurred in the past.
But almost immediately, excuses began to be heard.
“Most of the violence has been committed a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the 1990s and some in the early 21st century.
I mean, we are determined to punish these violent acts, but it will not be an easy task," he said.
However, in a June 5 interview for TIME, which took place in Jakarta, Wiranto claimed that he did not plan to implement any measures in Papua.
Instead, he said, “all cases will be brought before the court.”
Wiranto, who was accused by the UN of "crimes against humanity" based on more than 1,000 deaths during the 1999 independent elections in East Timor, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua have so far been settled, including the Pania incident.
The families of the victims of the shooting in Paniai welcomed his claims with distrust.
“I’ve been asked four times in the last three years, but so far I haven’t seen anything,” Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
As he says, a few years later he still lives in fear.
"I'm afraid," he says.
"I'm afraid the army will arrest me or someone will shoot me."
His brother Yacobus confirmed the view of many residents of Paniai, who are afraid to talk about the incident.
According to him, he was beaten by members of the army after helping to bury four of the victims.
"After the bodies were buried, the army started looking for me," he said.
The shooting has not stopped yet.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired at villagers in neighboring Deiyai.
The clash, in which one person died and another 17 were injured, occurred between the villagers and the manager of a construction company, who refused to provide assistance in transporting the man unconscious to the hospital.
Ravianus Douw (24), who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested outside the company building.
According to police, the villagers threw stones at them and the answers were a warning shot.
However, locals claim that the mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) started shooting at the crowd and killed one person.
"There was a panic, we were afraid of retaliation," 29-year-old Domingo Badia, who lives near the hospital and witnessed the arrival of the injured, told TIME.
“I didn’t leave the house for two days.”
The Deiyais parliament demanded the punishment of the police officers involved and the withdrawal of the mobile brigade from the area.
Paniai was always a thorn in the eye for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development only deepens the separation of the indigenous Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes, who live in the central highlands.
Many of them have joined the Papua Liberation Movement (OPM), an army of insurgents who protect the rights of Papuans by attacking and kidnapping Indonesian police officers.
Some of the leaders of the OPM come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
As a result of the attacks in recent years, the army has arrested and arbitrarily detained thousands of residents of Paniai, all under the pretext of "ensuring national sovereignty".
Some of them will never be seen again.
Paniai is known among the people of Papua as a “tragic and forgotten place”.
Poverty pours oil into the fire.
The little rice that is sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
Bread is just as unattainable.
The locals grow their food: mainly sweet potatoes, fruits and leafy vegetables.
Women work in the fields; each of them cultivates four or five fields with sweet potatoes.
Most of the harvest is intended for the needs of the family, the rest are sold in the local market.
Ten pieces of sweet potatoes cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Since Nabire Airport opened several air routes and new immigrants began flowing into the country, there has been an increase in economic inequality between native Papuans and immigrants.
Already so few jobs are usually occupied by more educated and richer immigrants.
Papuans rarely have the capital and education they need to start a business.
“Young people are moving out of villages because of a lack of jobs and money,” said John Gobai, Chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
Due to isolation, the province of Papua is hidden from the world.
Strict rules for foreign journalists also contribute to this.
Earlier this year, two French journalists - Franck Escudie and Basile Longchamp - were expelled from the papua for "lack of cooperation with the authorities", all despite the fact that they received such a rare filming permit.
Phelim Kine, the deputy director of the Asian branch of Human Rights Watch, promised Jokowi in his election campaign to abolish strict rules for journalists and achieve transparency and development, but this never happened.
“Foreign journalists working in the rebel easternmost regions of Papua and West Papua are at great risk: visa waivers and blacklisting,” the statement said.
The lack of reports from foreign journalists means that international pressure on Indonesia in the case of Papua is largely limited.
In March, six Pacific nations - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and the Solomon Islands - urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "diverse and widespread acts of violence" in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
These countries have also supported OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir shook the accusations when he told reporters in Jakarta: “In Indonesia, the democratic system still applies and the media is free, so it is difficult to mask evidence of human rights violations.”
Local people are calling for the participation of foreign governments.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by human rights envoy Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, the locals shouted, according to a source who also attended the meeting but wanted to remain anonymous, the slogan "we want freedom".
More elections are planned for 2019 in Indonesia, but the Papuans say they will not vote for Jokowi.
"Jokowi is a man who has good intentions but is surrounded by people associated with the shooting in Paniai," said Gobau, the tribal council chairman.
He wants Jokowi to know that the inhabitants of Paniai - in addition to living in constant fear of a robbery army - are wracked by poverty, poor education and the health care system.
Gobai claims that the residents of Pania, like the rest of the Papuans, consider their voice to be a “debt” that Joko has to pay.
“They don’t want money, they want justice,” he added.
Despite the threats and intimidation of the family of the victims of the Paniai shooting, they continue in the last symbolic act of defiance: they bury the bodies of the victims on the grounds opposite the police and military station.
Knowing that justice will never be done enough, at least it will not allow those responsible to forget their crimes.
"A member of our family was killed," Yacobus said with his head down.
"What can we do?"
