EPA Chief Scott Pruitt on the postponement of the planned directives to reduce emissions of the Obama administration
After the Environmental Protection Agency was sued by 15 states, its chief Scott Pruitt revoked his earlier decision to postpone the implementation of the former Obama administration’s plan to reduce carbon emissions.
Pruitt introduced changes to his plan, responding more flexibly than previous governments to the needs of state environmental regulators.
However, he did not mention the legal challenge filed against his previous position in the Federal Court of Appeal.
This is the latest date set for 1 October, when countries should start implementing the 2015 ground-level ozone regulation.
Pruitt announced in June that he would delay the deal by one year and order a more detailed study of the plan to avoid “interference with local decisions or threatening economic growth.”
Pruitt, who held the position of Oklahoma Attorney General prior to his appointment as EPA chief by President Donald Trump, has long served as a reliable opponent of tougher environmental regulations.
Since settling in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly moved or postponed regulations proposed by the chemical and fossil industries.
The sudden turnaround on Wednesday is the biggest legal failure for Pruitt’s regulatory agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA executive exceeded its authority in an effort to delay the Obama administration’s incorporation of a plan that required oil and gas companies to reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released on Wednesday night, Pruitt proposed its version of the ozone standards and strengthened the EPA’s commitment to cooperate with states through comprehensive processes and meeting new standards within a given time frame.
“The previous administration of the EPA often failed to meet deadlines and waited for it to be sued by activist groups and others, agreeing to settle and further set plans,” said Pruitt, who has filed more than a dozen lawsuits with the EPA in his previous position.
“We don’t believe in regulation through litigation and we take compliance seriously.
We never joke about our status and the authority that comes from it.”
However, the EPA statement states that Pruitt may at some point use “the possibility of delay and all other legally available authorities” to ensure that regulation “will be based on sound policies and the most available information.”
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader overhaul of the ozone rules.
The White House budget approved last month seeks to postpone the implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The measure has not yet passed the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led the coalition of states suing the EPA this week, said the group does not intend to allow legal pressure.
"Addressing the EPA's views - following our judicial review - is an important health and safety victory for the 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans who are directly affected by air pollution," Schneiderman said in a statement.
New York was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington and Washington, D.C.
Ground-level ozone occurs when common harmful substances released by cars, power plants, oil refineries, chemical power plants and other sources react in the atmosphere with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause severe breathing problems in sensitive people and thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists are applauding Pruitt’s sudden change.
“It’s troubling how much pressure needs to be exerted to change the minds of responsible people and protect the air we breathe,” said Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to struggle with the Trump administration’s ideological drive to help polluters and special interests.”
