There are no tourists in China.
Beijing loses billions due to visa policy.
For decades, China has been trying to exert its influence without the use of force.
It spends $10 billion a year to support language schools and build universities abroad, pushes its entertainment industry to foreign markets, and seeks to attract Western tourists.
Beijing is not going to do that.
The state media there talk about the plan to make tourism the driving force of economic transformation and modernization.
Last year, however, the number of arrivals increased by just 3.8 percent and about 80 percent of tourists to China came from Hong Kong, Macau and Taiwan.
This is due, among other things, to the fact that despite all its global aspirations, China does not welcome foreigners with open arms, assessing the situation in the most populous country in the world, Professor of Economics from the University of Beijing Christopher Balding in an article for Bloomberg.
An example that speaks for everything is the Chinese visa policy.
Only 13 countries have visa-free relations with China, the citizens of the other countries have to get their visas in advance.
Therefore, in the Chinese authorities in the US, the crowds are comparable to the celebrations of the Chinese New Year.
The visa costs $140, but if you don’t want to wait for long hours in line, you have to pay $100 or more for additional services.
Such restrictions create significant economic hurdles.
A study by the Journal of Economics and Finance found that the need for a visa reduces the number of visitors to the country by 70 percent.
In 2015, only two million Americans visited mainland China, while Hong Kong, which accounts for less than three percent of China’s gross domestic product and lives in less than one percent of the country’s population, visited 1.8 million Americans.
China often deepens this problem itself when it uses tourism to achieve its political goals, for example in disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China cut traffic to South Korea in the spring as part of a rift around the South Korean anti-missile system, the South Koreans retaliated and avoided China.
In May, the number of visits fell by 42 percent year-on-year, while Japan saw an increase of 85 percent.
All of this has an impact on macroeconomic stability.
According to a recent report by the U.S. central bank Fed, China could leave as much as $190 billion as a result of Chinese foreign travel, while China receives about $35 billion a year as part of the sale of currency to incoming tourists.
According to the official figures on the development of the balance of payments, China had a deficit of $217 billion in tourism last year, which is equal to 44 percent of the total Chinese surplus in trade in goods.
A small number of tourists, therefore, inflict a very painful blow on a country that is anxiously preventing the outflow of capital.
However, the factors mentioned above are only one manifestation of more general restraint towards foreigners.
In many parts of China, virtually no one has heard of immigrants.
In 2013, fewer than a million foreigners lived in China.
In the United States, there are several cities.
Even Japan, which is not exactly a crossroads of immigration, has doubled.
A number of scientific papers show that immigrants usually revive economic growth, entrepreneurship and innovation.
You won’t find them in China.
Solving these problems will be politically challenging, but the step offered is to simplify the visa system.
Other Asian countries, particularly India and Vietnam, have been making great efforts lately to simplify and reduce visa procedures.
If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currency, it should be easier for them to get there.
