“We demand prosecution and closure of the case, we want peace of mind and reconciliation, but justice above all,” Brooks said.
Until then, the process of healing and reconciliation cannot begin.
On July 27, 1946, a forensic doctor covered one of the bodies of the victims of the lynching at Moore's Ford.
According to FBI records obtained by NBC News, up to 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were expected to participate in the lynching.
No one has been prosecuted so far.
Despite the fact that the suspects remain at large for decades, civil rights advocates claim that both the reasons for lynching - politics and sex - were known to all residents of the city.
In April 1946, the Supreme Court of Georgia granted black citizens of Georgia the right to participate in elections scheduled for the summer for the first time.
And it was during the summer election period, according to the FBI, black-skinned farmer Roger Malcolm had stabbed the owner of white-skinned estates, Barnett Hester, during a fight — allegedly because of his wife.
According to Brooks, it was rumored in the city that Hester was hanging out with Malcolm's wife Dorothy and brought her into a different state.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, the then prominent white-skinned landowner Loy Harrison bailed Malcolm in the amount of $600.
