Latest results of tests to determine the age limit for asylum applications in Sweden
The latest results of asylum-seekers in Sweden who have been subjected to a new method of assessing their age show that over 80 percent of people were surveyed as older than 18, but not everyone believes their accuracy.
The Swedish Forensic Medical Agency (R<0xC3><0x83><0xC2><0xA4>ttsmedicinalverket) began carrying out new tests at the beginning of this year.
The aim of the method is to more accurately assess applicants in the context of the assessment of asylum applications. The measure was acceded after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticised for failing to determine the correct age of some refugees who lied about their age.
To date, the Swedish Migration Agency has submitted 6,880 cases to investigate, and the Forensic Medical Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests carried out from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
80 percent (2002) were assessed as over 18 years old, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medical Agency found that the respondent was “possibly over 18 years old.”
In another 423 cases, it was decided that the respondent was “possibly under 18 years of age”.
The tests shall be accessed only if the age of the questioned person is questionable.
According to Johan G<0xC3><0x83><0xC2><0xB6>ransson of the Forensic Medical Agency, the results correspond to the previous month.
"Compared to last month, the statistics are on track and the numbers are very similar," he told The Local.
The higher number of applicants whose age was estimated to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that applicants for asylum are lying about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and stated that in 442 cases, it was found that "the person in question is 18 years of age or older."
The newspaper Svenska Dagbladet investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases the respondent stated that he would be 18 this year.
Critics also criticized the medical method of determining age, which includes x-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of knee joints, which are subsequently assessed by dentists and x-ray specialists.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, who, among other things, deals with assessing the biological maturity of people to determine the age at which they went through puberty.
“I had reason to think about this issue and I don’t think these types of measurements to assess age are right.
The assessment of biological age is, in a sense, very uncertain.
If we can’t determine the age with precision, we shouldn’t pretend otherwise,” he told Metro.
The forensic medical agency Agency's G<0xC3><0x83><0xC2><0xB6>ransson defended the decision, saying: "In general, the risk of misjudging a child as an adult is small.
The highest risk is the fact that the respondent is just below the age of 18, which in this case corresponds to 10 percent of all respondents.
