NHS Prescribes Controversial HIV Drug to 10,000 Patients
Patients will have access to ‘transformative’ HIV prevention treatment since September, based on the Supreme Court’s decision on funding the NHS drug.
The English National Health Service (NSH) has announced that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through the health service to approximately 10,000 patients within a three-year trial period.
The NSH agreed to fund the trial after the appeals court upheld last year’s Supreme Court decision stating that the NHS has the funds to pay for PrEP despite a statement that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, which was announced on Thursday, was taken by NHS England from the mouth of CEO Simon Stevens as a “significant intervention,” while the National AIDS Trust (NAT) described the decision as a “decisive moment.”
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start receiving patients. Other clinics will join in October and by April 2018 will be fully implemented across England.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV drug given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among at-risk patients.
The application of PrEP before sex means that there is a sufficient number of specific drugs in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These drugs can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Among the patients tested were gay or bisexual men, transgender people and people with HIV-positive partners who were not treated successfully.
The clinics will identify eligible participants who will sign consent to participate in the testing, including men, women, transgender people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with a GP in the UK can also apply to their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program will bring taxpayers to <0xC2><0xA3>10 million and NHS England has signed a drug distribution contract this week after obtaining an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: “This important intervention should complement and fully leverage the ever-expanding and increasingly successful effort to prevent HIV.
It’s another milestone in a more than 30-year effort to stop one of the biggest challenges to human health.”
Deborah Gold, executive director of the National AIDS Trust (NAT), said: “We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and to patients at risk, it will offer the possibility of transforming the English HIV epidemic.
From September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will lead to improved quality of life for many.
We welcome this statement with pleasure.”
Ian Green, executive director of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: “The number one priority must be the rapid deployment of tests across the country; we must ensure its availability to every patient.
We now have the trial drug PrEP available, and we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection.”
Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: “The beginning of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will bring us a step closer to a full understanding of the benefits of PrEP.
“It is now important that we start testing as soon as possible across the country to protect people who are exposed to HIV and, together, to stop the spread of HIV in society.”
