“I used to live with my ex-husband in a much larger house in Knightsbridge,” Joanne said.
“I was looking for something at a more reasonable price.
I ran into this apartment in Earls Court and it had the same ceiling height.
I immediately fell in love with him and nodded at him the same day."
Since then, the apartment of the size of 1000 square meters has undergone a complete renovation.
One-room apartment with a complicated layout - to get into the bedroom, you had to walk through the kitchen - wanted Joanne to add storage spaces and mezzanine to use the high ceiling.
“I longed for a high ceiling, large windows and plenty of light.
Those were my demands," she said.
For this purpose, she employed Erfana Azadi from the Duck & Shed design and design studio based in Notting Hill and used the nearly four-meter ceiling to create a home that was not just a project but also a place to live.
The ceiling did not reach such a height that two gaps could climb over each other - the challenge for architects was to create a mezzanine on which one could walk upright.
Erfan had to engage his creative thinking.
“The steel structure is quite complicated,” he explained.
“We had to arrange both spaces so that we could walk upright.
It wasn’t just about building a simple platform, but also bending the steel structure to make it at the right height above and below the ceiling.”
This arrangement allowed Erfan to construct two full-fledged rooms on himself - and at the same time add drama.
The mezzanine overlooks the beautiful living room of an old copper window frame in the design of Retrouvius.
Mirror furniture in gold color, silver line and retro chandelier Serge Mouille creates a unique style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in drama, space and lighting.
The short corridor is equipped with mirrors on both sides and looks so longer.
The mirror bar in the kitchen looks like a window to another room.
At the front door there are storage rooms equipped with mirrors for storing utensils and glasses.
The advantage of the living room, which gives the whole apartment the impression of a significantly larger space, is the ability to separate it from the kitchen, if not used.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
What is unique about this solution, however, are the folding doors.
"We had to solve the technical side," Erfan says of the reinforced veneered doors.
"The door is equipped with counterweights to play very easily."
Thanks to the smart use of space and storage space, Joanne gained an additional 16 square meters, a second room and a better overall layout of the apartment.
"When it comes down to it, what you're selling is the living space - or the valuation of your property," Erfan said.
"A real estate agent basically calculates his price on the basis of the living space when he enters the apartment."
In this case, it was possible to increase the living area while maintaining quality materials that give the space a luxurious appearance.
“The material is very important because you touch it and create an emotional bond with your home,” Erfan added.
“You don’t like the electricity in the walls.
Yes, they are important, but your heart won’t win.”
As it turned out, a quality design and an increase in living space can turn an ordinary apartment into an exceptional work.
And just like Joanne, you can eventually decide to stay.
