Maybe John F. Kelly can actually do it.
If so, it will be the first.
Politico said the new White House chief of staff plans to curb the flow of President Trump’s information — including reports in television news — in the hopes of keeping Trump on the ground.
Here is the report by Josh Dawsey:
“When the new White House Chief of Staff John F. Kelly met for the first day in office with the staff, he outlined a key issue for the Trump White House that he intends to fix: misinformation that gets into the hands of the president.
Kelly told employees that he had to personally approve all the information — whether on paper or in a spoken word — because the president could make better decisions based on the right information.”
Kelly’s diagnosis actually makes sense, but many of his predecessors have cracked their teeth at checking Trump and his media appearances.
Trump’s relationship with the media dates back several decades – and now that he’s sitting in the White House, his habit of watching TV news is even stronger.
“If Trump as a candidate was upset by honest reporting, it was appropriate for him to show that he was being talked about in a positive light by a lot of other media outlets that were easier to convince,” Sam Nunberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February.
Tara Palmeri of Politico wrote at the time that “the key to keeping Trump’s tweets on the line – at least according to the words of six former campaign organizers – is to ensure that Trump regularly monitors the media that praises him.”
All right.
But the idea that Trump’s tendency to post his views on Twitter has ever been “under control” is ridiculous.
Maybe these campaigners know something that others don’t know — that Trump’s tweets would be more outrageous if someone didn’t check them.
The tweets that Trump never sent out are unlikely to be heard.
If his employees managed to keep him in check at least several times, then their efforts did not go to waste.
But so far, no one has been able to regularly prevent Trump from inciting controversial issues.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, which is made up of rival factions, people are regularly trying to strengthen their agenda by spurring Trump’s materials — which may, but may not be reliable — that support their view of the world.
Politico, which covered the issue from all sides, published a report in May on the inclination of advisers to submit dubious information to the head of state.
This is an example of such information from the pen of reporter Shane Goldmacher:
“Contemporary and former Trump officials claim that the president often responds very angryly to negative news from the media, especially reports of information leaks, and seeks to find their origin.
The situation came at the end of February when someone tipped the president a copy of an article from GotNews.com — the website of provocateur Charles C. Johnson — that accused Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Walsh of being “the source of many leaks” from the White House.
Notwithstanding that Johnson was forever expelled from Twitter for harassment; or that he did not substantiate his claims with any evidence; or that he had already published false accusations in the past and later retracted them.
Trump read the article and started asking about Walsh.
Goldmacher added that then-Chief of Staff Reince Priebus and White House Secretary Rob Porter “were trying to implement a system to administer and document the information that President Trump will receive.”
Would it work?
Kelly is now, three months later, trying to enforce the same strategy.
He may prove to be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump’s impulsiveness just doesn’t go away and his aides are still competing for power.
These immutable factors will certainly make Kelly's mission more difficult.
