Michelle Carter Sentenced for Sending Text Messages Inciting Conrad Roy's Suicide
A Massachusetts woman has been sentenced to two years in prison for inciting her boyfriend to commit suicide through text messages and phone calls.
20-year-old Michelle Carter is sentenced to 15 months in prison and then to five years in parole.
Carter was convicted in June of the unintentional murder of Conrad Roy, who took his own life on July 13, 2014.
Roy’s father told the court on Thursday: “The whole family is crushed.
My son was my best friend.”
Carter was left at large until the decision was made.
She was threatened with up to 20 years in prison, but her lawyers argued that she and Roy suffered from mental illness.
Dressed in red pants and cream blouses, Carter stood at the scene of her verdict, with tears in her eyes, her hands clenched, and her eyes turned to the ground.
"Her actions killed Conrad Roy," the plaintiff told the judge.
“She ended his life to relieve herself.
She could not accept her own responsibility," she said.
"She didn't show any remorse."
Carter’s attorney, however, said it was “unfortunate circumstances that he deeply regrets.”
Judge Lawrence Moniz added that “her age or level of maturity or even mental disorder does not have a significant impact on her conduct.”
The plaintiff read Roy’s mother Lynn Roy’s statement: “There won’t be a single day before I grieve over the loss of my son.
I want him to be proud of me - I take care of his sisters and together we will endure the immense pain that we will carry with us forever," the statement said.
Roy's sister Camdy Roy testified that she was "stalked" by the knowledge that she would never attend her brother's wedding and would never be his children's aunt.
"The loss of the person I've seen since I was born is the pain I'll carry with me for life," she said.
The state of Massachusetts does not have a valid law that would affect a person assisting in the suicide of another person. This case thus establishes a legal precedent.
Carter was 17 years old when Roy was found in a car seat in 2014 poisoned by carbon dioxide.
The case attracted the attention of the entire nation after Carter's text messages were published that incited suicide.
“Perhaps hanging out, jumping out of a building, or getting stabbed, I don’t care,” Carter wrote in text messages sent just two weeks before he died when Roy was on family vacation.
A few minutes before her suicide, she wrote to him, "You have to do it, Conrad" and "Just throw in the generator and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Moniz said Carter had longed for attention through Roy's death and ordered her to refrain from commenting in the press.
The case raised many questions.
One of the people who sided with Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted of murdering her British roommate in Italy in 2007. She was acquitted two years ago.
Ms. Knox (30) published a statement in the Los Angeles Times: “Michelle Carter deserves understanding and help, not prison.”
