Lavender from Provence threatens climate change
Lavender has become a symbol of Provence in southeastern France, but is now threatened by climate change.
Lavender is declining as a result of dry climate and harmful insects, causing horror on the faces of researchers and farmers looking for a solution.
Eric Chaisse, an expert at the CRIEPPAM Agricultural Research Institute in Provence, said: “The cultivation of lavender in Provence is at risk because in the last few years this plant has been exposed to climate change, which brings less rainfall in spring and autumn.
This affects the life of lavender.
It is also the fault of cicadas and mosquitoes carrying micro-bacteria that thrive in dry climates.”
There's a lot at stake.
Lavender attracts tourists and the oil produced from it is an important ingredient in perfumes and cosmetics.
Eric Chaisse said: “Instead of long and beautiful flowers grow smaller, undeveloped and often weaker plants.
The amount of oil obtained from these lavenders is, of course, smaller."
A possible solution may be more efficient water distribution and slowing the evaporation of water from the soil, but also spraying lavender with a protective mixture of clay and water and breeding more species resistant to dry weather.
