Dinosaurs used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, however frightening.
Researchers have now uncovered the first findings of an amazing rhino-sized creature whose perfectly preserved remains — which experts have dubbed the ‘Mona Lisa of Dinosaurs’ — have been found by a Canadian miner.
The remains were preserved to such an extent that experts were able to determine the reddish-brown color of his scaly skin and stated that the dinosaur had a ‘problematic past’.
An article in the journal Current Biology said it was “the most preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the best dinosaur species in the world.”
The fossil is a new species in the genus Nodosauridae. Dinosaurs lived in the Cretaceous period, about 110 to 112 million years ago.
His perfectly preserved condition was literally shocked by the researchers, who described him with the words ‘really remarkable’.
The armored beetle is, according to National Geographic, the best-preserved fossil of its kind to date.
Behind the discovery is Shawn Funk, who discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011, while drilling in the Suncor Millenium mine near Canadian Alberta.
He stumbled upon something that looked like a foreign object and decided to explore it more closely.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
The researchers spent the next six years working to discover an animal from a huge piece of land weighing 1,100 kg.
After the work is completed, the dinosaur is ready to be discovered.
"Just blink your eyes a little and you'll believe he's asleep," said Caleb Brown, the head of the work and a naturalist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the animal is on display.
“It will certainly go down in history as one of the most beautiful and well-preserved species of dinosaur – the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.”
By studying his skin, the researchers found that this herbivore — despite being covered in armor and resembling a walking tank — was most likely facing a serious threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect against predators and used a masking system used by many animals today.
Experts say that it allowed him to blend better with his surroundings and avoid enemies. The masking system suggests that he was a favorite food of larger dinosaurs.
Reports of a 110-million-year-old dinosaur of the genus Nodosauridae first appeared in the paper in May. It is currently available for inspection at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The researchers named it Borealopelto markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, who spent more than 7,000 hours with the team carefully uncovering the fossil.
Thanks to the amazingly preserved state of the fossil, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to document the patterns and shapes of scales and armor throughout the body.
They uncovered a method of masking commonly used by modern-day animals in defense – the top of the animal was darker than its bottom.
Although this masking effect is common in nature, the findings of the researchers are surprising, because the size of Borealopelta far exceeds today's animals using the same technique.
Thus, it is possible that the dinosaur was so many predators that evolution preferred masking over confrontation to survival.
Many modern-day mascots—such as deer, zebras, and or hares—are much smaller and also more vulnerable than prey, suggesting that the nosodaurus had to fight for its survivors literally.
"The predation of a huge and heavily armored dinosaur vividly illustrates the dangers that predators posed during the Cretaceous period," Brown said.
A chemical analysis of the organic components contained in the scales also revealed that the dinosaur skin was likely reddish-brown in color.
Researchers continue to study the animal and search for more information about its life, including the preserved stomach contents, to find out its last meal.
They believe that the dinosaur fell into the river after death and was taken to the sea, where it sank to the bottom.
Alberta had the same climate as Florida at the time, and rivers and oceans stretched much further inland than they do today.
“This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered in perfectly preserved scaly skin while being preserved in three dimensions so we can see its original size,” Brown said.
For these reasons, the animal looks practically the same as in the time of the Cretaceous.
You don’t have to use your imagination to reconstruct it; just blink your eyes a little and it seems like you’re just sleeping.’
During the Cretaceous period, huge theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs, were walking on two legs.
Although the king of all dinosaurs - Tyrannosaurus rex - lived several million years after Borealopelta, this armored dinosaur could have been a favorite prey of his equally terrible ancestors.
These include Acrocanthosaurus, an 11.5-metre-long monster weighing over 6 tons.
Researchers, whose latest findings were published in the journal Current Biology, believe that Borealopelt’s body was floated into the sea after being mummified in the mud.
Behind the discovery is Shawn Funk, who discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011, while drilling at the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including leather and armor, which is also complete from chin to hip.
The animal reached an average length of 5 meters and weighed up to 1300 kg.
From his shoulders protruded two 50 cm axes.
Researchers believe that this herbivore roamed the territory of present-day Canada until it ended up in the river that washed it into the sea.
His underwater tomb kept his body in perfect condition.
Fossil remains of this species are also preserved to the extent that the armored plates around the skull still cover the remains of the skin.
As Michael Greshko wrote for National Geographic, ‘finding such a preserved individual can be compared to winning a lottery.
The longer I follow him, the more shocking the find seems to me.
