How did one activist learn the answer to the question, ‘Whose Streets?’
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell shook her whole body.
A day after arriving in New York, a St. Louis parent sat on the bed in an Airbnb room and scrolled through Facebook posts on her phone.
She came across a contribution from a high school student.
"Police have just shot an 18-year-old boy whose body is still lying on the street," he said.
She was surprised that no one else wrote her this post, so she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
<0x40>TheePharoah constantly retweeted her wall posts.
A rapper from St. Louis tweeted about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old boy who was shot dead by a white-skinned police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown's body lying powerless on the street, where no one had taken him for four hours.
"That's crazy," Ferrell thought.
Death, however, was nothing new to her and her community.
She put down her phone to come back to him the night she watched tweets about people gathering on Canfield Drive.
One of the men claimed to be the victim's father and held a sign with the words "Ferguson police killed my unarmed son" in his hand!
She was watching live news — one of the policemen was standing in front of a group of protesters, holding a lead in his hand and on his other end a barking dog.
In another video, another policeman, she said, held a gun in his hand, aimed at the crowd and shouted, “I’ll kill you all...animals.”
"That's not normal," Ferrell said to herself.
“This is not the kind of murder we’re used to and we can call normal.
I felt goose bumps all over my body.
“I was angry and I was crying.”
She immediately booked a return flight and the next day left for her home.
After landing at 11:00 p.m., she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father and decided to go to Ferguson in the morning.
The story of what happened to Ferrell and the city of Ferguson over the next three years is described in a new documentary "Whose Streets?", which will be released in theaters on August 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, love and resistance, strength and integrity told from the perspective of the people living in the community, who go out into the streets and ask for answers.
On her way to Ferguson, Ferrell introduced a dialogue with her daughter - dressed in a floral shirt and the same floral earrings - about a topic they had discussed many times before - "about the experience with blacks".
“Do you remember how I taught you how black people had to fight for what they believed in?” he recalls.
"We're going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that's not right."
"I didn't think I'd take it with me," Ferrell said later.
“Today’s events are the culmination... of what happened in the past.
She had to know it and see it with her own eyes and grow up in it.
She needed to develop not only in activism and organization, but at the same time she had to know the difference between the different layers of experience with blacks and what we need to do to free ourselves.
Although I am able to provide her with conditions in which she will not experience racism on her own skin, she is in no way different from any other black child-woman.
I feel that if I had protected her from this experience, I would have only harmed her.”
Upon arriving in Ferguson, the first stop on South Florissant Road was opposite the police department, which became the base of activists who expected police officer Darren Wilson's words about his possible involvement in the incident.
Here, Ferrell and her daughter met a local businessman who prepared food for others.
Together, they packed food in bags and helped spread it to the Protestants.
In Ferrell’s eyes, a new type of activism was slowly born.
"My activism turned upside down after August 9th," Ferrell said, adding that while studying at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was the president of the Minority Student Nurses Assn. and was striving to introduce health care and food into Black communities.
“I had no experience with the organization.
It was natural."
A few weeks later, during an evening demonstration, Ferrell met the later co-director of the documentary, Sabaah Folayan.
Folayan said he and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar wanted to "only document" the events.
But Ferrell thought, "Are you working on a document or are you trying to find a story to use?"
This kind of skepticism penetrated into the community through many people, often whites, who wanted to make money on pain and determination.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview: “We have heard that the voices of people born and raised in Ferguson are very often neglected and that we wanted to change.”
Folayana has already partnered with co-director Damon Davis, a renowned local artist who deals with the topic of death row inmates.
His participation in the project also included Ferrell and six other locals who were followed by the Whose Streets team in the years following Brown's murder.
"No one is speaking for us in this document, but it is our statement," Davis said.
“It was important to me — how these people will be represented — because I will be represented in the same way.”
While the aim of the document was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences - in an effort to show that the movement "is not about a rescue leader, but about bringing the community closer together," Folayana said - it turned out that she was the most open to participating in filming.
"Whose Streets?" describes a very personal aspect of Ferrell's life, such as how he fell in love with his wife.
"I felt naked," Ferrell said with a smile on her face as she thought of the first moment she saw the final version of the document.
“But I understood that in order to do this job and polish the blacks, I had to open up.”
Ferrell’s story also highlights the role of an eccentric black woman in the broader aspect of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement - who created a social media campaign under #BlackLivesMatter in response to the 2012 killing of teenager Trayvon Martin - call themselves weirdos.
“Black eccentric women in leadership positions ultimately stand behind maintaining the movement,” Ferrell said, “because we are constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black eccentric women must bear the brunt of these events.”
Folayana agrees with this statement, adding that "the movement is actually supported by black women and a lot of eccentric black women."
However, she insists that "this is not just an affirmative matter" and Ferrell is not the main hero of the document because of her views.
"It was she who was the driving force and the source of energy," she said.
“That she was in the front lines is no coincidence, because life at these crossroads in the skin of a black weirdo woman is dangerous.
You can feel the energy in front of the screen.”
Meanwhile, back in Ferguson, television station cameras have cleared their positions, but severe racial ties between the community and the police persist.
Ferrell is serving a two-and-a-half-year sentence for blocking the highway during demonstrations.
She described the social-political atmosphere in the area she calls home as “Disorder.”
However, she does not stop in her efforts, which she has been committed to since she took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We need to love and support each other.
“The only thing we can lose is our chains.”
