A Becoming Resemblance: Artist Creates Portraits Using Chelsea Manning’s DNA
In the middle of one of the rooms of the Fridman Gallery in New York, there are several faces of different shades of skin - white, black and brown - hung from the ceiling on the wires, each of them as if it fell out of the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from mouthwashes and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where a former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized publication of secret cables on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is titled A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her experience in technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a transgender and pioneering dissident whose sentence was reduced by Obama three days before he resigned as president of the United States.
Through an algorithmic analysis of Manning’s DNA and the use of 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a sharp, if not intellectual commentary on the susceptibility of DNA – as well as on the many ways in which DNA can be interpreted by such an identity – and a non-intelligible one.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, has spoken of herself as a woman since she was young, and was convicted in 2013 on 20 counts, including a violation of six espionage laws, computer fraud and theft.
All of her photographs were detained by prison staff, and only one lower-quality black and white photograph was leaked to the public, on which Manning, visibly concerned, sat in the driver's seat in a platinum blonde wig, with which she is now associated.
In 2015, there were still positive reactions to the 2012 Dewey-Hagborg project Stranger Visions.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create an image of possible forms of these people.
And it was at this time that she received an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
“They were planning an interview with Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to complement the article with a portrait,” Dewey-Hagborg said at the opening of the new exhibition.
Visits and photography were not allowed, however, so they turned to Chelsea to ask if she was interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse met each other over the course of two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoila Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were pardoned and could attend the exhibition in person.
In fact, a few days after the release of the comic, President Obama asked for Manning’s release, which was a welcome change after several unbearable years spent in a military prison in Kansas.
It is indeed interesting that the exhibition is taking place right at a time when Donald Trump is waging war with people who are seeking to publish government information and transgender soldiers, while trying to find new ways to incite resentment with his tweets in areas he should support.
In response to a question about this particular timing, Dewey-Hagborg stated that "everything happens for some reason."
Under the artist’s statement on one of the walls of the gallery, Manning calls with her huge signature (the letter “i” in the name is sculpted by the heart) after the end of “self-serving factionalism based on gender, race, sexuality and culture”.
On the opposite side are sequences of its mitochondrial DNA - centipedes of the letters C, G and A recorded by a pencil.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the sophisticated scientific dictionary of the artist), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
"I hope people will take away from this that our genome doesn't care about who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it their own way," said Dewey-Hagborg. Her 2007 work Spurious Memories is also on the topic of video.
“DNA tells a lot of different stories, this is 30 of them.”
The last copy of the exhibition, placed in a separate room, is the only page from the above graphic novel.
It depicts Manning emerging as King Kong from the United States Disciplinary Barracks with a megaphone in his hand.
"As soon as they stop you from speaking, they win," it says.
“Never let yourself be silenced.”
"It's a direct copy of one of the letters," said the Philadelphia artist.
"When I think about it, my goose bumps."
Manning has not yet personally attended the exhibition - as predicted in the comic - but when it does, she will be greeted in the middle of the room with her masks, her own genome-like images, sorted like a mob of Protestants.
This was also the purpose of the exhibition, including the nearly 160 cm tall statue of Maninga, on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded in pencil.
"They were placed on the walls in the past, but this time I wanted to make them feel crowded," Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
“I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement that takes the form of Chelsea and liberates her.”
