"In the near future, we will complete the WADA plan" - Russian Deputy Prime Minister Mutko
Deputy Prime Minister Vitaly Mutko said it would not take long to implement the remaining criteria of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) and the re-establishment of the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA).
Some of the criteria of the new plan have already been completed and RUSADA has already acquired the right to plan and test in cooperation with the UK Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
With this in mind, WADA’s plan has been updated,” Mutko said on Thursday.
The Vice-President commented on the second part of WADA's plan to comply with the Code - which describes the criteria for the renewal of RUSADA - which was recently published on the organization's website.
According to Mutka, the code does not contain anything that should concern Russia.
“Everything has been announced and everything will be implemented.
The results will be available to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA in the near future," he added.
One of the criteria, however, calls for a public announcement of the results of the WADA investigation, which was investigated by Richard McLaren, about alleged sponsorship of doping by Russian athletes by the government.
Mutko said: “We are conducting an investigation because our anti-doping system has obviously failed.
All measures have been agreed upon.
However, there were no state programs in our country, so we cannot admit to something that never existed.”
Mutkov’s words were confirmed by Vitaly Smirnov, director of the Russian Independent Public Anti-Doping Commission.
In an interview with Russia’s RSport, Smirnov acknowledged the problems of Russian anti-doping agents, but added: “On many occasions, we have stated that the report contains controversial positions and regulations.
No one plans to accept the report completely without reservation," Smirnov concluded.
WADA suspected RUSADU of carrying out doping checks within Russia in November 2015 immediately before the doping scandal.
The organization, however, allowed planning and unification of testing under the supervision of international experts and the UK Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD) in June this year.
Following a visit to the organization’s Moscow headquarters in July, WADA Director-General Olivier Niggli said RUSADA was “on track” to resumption.
