Startups that will help your company not become another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the employee satisfaction rate of her e-commerce startup, but she did not find a suitable survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, useless, or even misleading.
And despite promising the anonymity of the survey, some employees expressed their distrust of the whole process.
“I was looking for consistency and objectivity,” said Errett, owner of the San Francisco-based Madison Reed hair care e-commerce company, which employs 75 people.
She asked for help from outside.
New start-ups from the human resources sector are constantly appearing on the market, helping companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with the specific purpose of measuring employee responsibilities, startups allow companies to conduct quick voting, target specific teams and demographic groups, and also offer complete employee anonymity and a hotline for filing complaints.
“There are tools like Strava and Fitbit on the market that track your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?” said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said that thanks to Glint, she gained more awareness of what her employees think and feel in three years.
In addition to quick surveys and voting of specific teams, Glint offers a company temperature map and a passing overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of low-rated managers - allowing the user to work on the fix.
Companies are beginning to realize that it is necessary to take care of the culture of the work environment - in case they become another Uber - which is frowned upon in scandals after a former employee posted on his blog a post describing the corporate environment and harassment of employees who are open to bullying.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys represents a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the Let’s Talk Payments website, which deals with technical and financial progress, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance industry could exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
Denver-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small surge in interest and activity earlier this year, just before the Uber scandals.
Almost 600 of Convertent’s customers include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber has also recently taken over the board.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable “blitz” surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
If the Director-General is involved in the problem, complaints are sent directly to the Management Board.
“The Court of Public Opinion has regulators,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of startup Convercent.
If the company is convicted of mistreatment of its employees or unethical behavior — and if regulators do not intervene — it may face costly consequences as a result of customer boycotts, employee exhaustion, or court proceedings, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant network, which employs more than 25,000 people across 500 locations, uses Convercent for more than a year to raise employees’ awareness of corporate policies and procedures and ensure an easy way to contact corporate management.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report any problem, he had to search the phone number or email to the company’s management, officially file a complaint, and hope for a successful solution.
It was often a frightening and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, Ruby Tuesday’s deputy general counsel, who said there had been no reliable way to track employee complaints before.
Now that the company uses Convercent, it ensures quick detection and resolution of problems that have never before reached managers sitting in offices, miles away from the real solution to complaints - such as discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
“It comes close to a holistic, overall view of employee experience,” said Vitrano, who runs Ruby Tuesday’s risk management group.
“We are protecting shareholders from litigation on the part of employees.”
Companies stopped taking employee ethics, values, and participation lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed following Enron’s downfall over employee ethical rights abuses, Quinlan said.
But it wasn’t until “you’ve got the whole thing covered in social media,” that companies began to realize that in the online world they can’t just hide their skeletons in a closet.
“Before people started using technology to track ethics, they relied on faith,” Quinlan added.
Glint and Convercent offer their software in the form of a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It is a business model and an opportunity that is endorsed by the bold capital investors who have supported both startups.
