The Making of a Graphic Novel: The Story of A Castle in England
The small castle of Scotney Castle recently played a major role in the music video for the band Squeeze, and Margaret Thatcher took refuge in it during the 70s and 80s of the last century.
Scotney, however, witnessed 700 years of turbulent history from his cozy spot on the Bewl River in British Kent, inspiring the curly Jamie Rhodes of York County – known for his fondness for historical documents – to create a graphic novel.
“Looking at the writing of a man who is 300 years after his death fascinates me,” Rhodes says with a serious face.
“When I hold a letter in my hands, I feel a personal connection.”
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of families who lived at Scotney Castle from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian period. Each story is illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
However, this is not Rhodes' first book inspired by archives: he is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection of British Library-inspired documents - a project that was very emotional for him.
“I was struck by a fingerprint on a letter written by a double agent in the 1970s who worked for the Jacobites,” he said.
"That's his fingerprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days you had to light a candle to read.
When I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm back in time.
I love the archives!”
For someone who is so fascinated by old papers, the support of the National Trust and Arts Council England and the opportunity to spend almost four months at the castle is almost like a dream.
Rhodes spent time exploring the Victorian "new" castle, browsing the archives, and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of a hyena on the wall and bottles that had been thrown into the ditch for centuries.
He walked around the land, exploring the ruins of the old castle, talking to the landlords, gardeners, and occasionally also with the artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
At night, he drank whiskey and sang.
The confidential history of Scotney is relatively unknown, as the National Trust only gained access to documents in 2006 after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived on the scene ten years later, the employees were only beginning to penetrate the archives that Rhodes described in words, as if “the aristocrats of many centuries were throwing their hands at the words: ‘Take it to the attic.’”
Diaries, letters from the times of the British Empire, maps depicting property: "You may think the dispute over land is boring," Rhodes said, "but I came across one case where two families were dragging on a birch.
Let go of those people!"
Some stories in the book use the castle as a springboard and dig deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the English uprising of 1381.
“I found a record of a rebellion at a castle in 1380, which was called the Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex in the book,” Rhodes said.
“The English uprising actually started in this area and I thought the uprising was a good starting point.
Maybe they have something to do with each other in the end.”
Other stories are closely linked to the history of the castle - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest, whom Darrell's family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was only discovered a few years after the coffin was discovered).
Rhodes's favorite family is the Darrells: "I was fascinated by the male generation - the men of that time were always indebted and spent money on things they couldn't afford.
The different generations of the Darrells dealt with it by marrying rich or old ladies - I imagine they were the handsome gentlemen who liked to wave their heads at the heirs."
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes searches for more adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week stay in the Finnish wilderness, where he inspired his next book on Elämämäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that was absorbed by nature.
This is a special place for Scotney.
"I was sad when I left," he said.
"I was like, 'Now I'm going to go back to real life.'"
