Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can alleviate the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
However, a new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million U.S. residents and 300,000 patients in the U.K., causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to consume meat and dairy products to alleviate symptoms, but researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps to build immune cells that support intestinal resistance.
The head of the study, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure the removal of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging the sensitive tissue.
Once the bowls of the scales tilt to the side of inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
As part of the research, the researchers found the presence of immune cells that support the body’s tolerance in the stomach of mice with a specific bacterium.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to form cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We found a link between one species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a common part of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that support the body's tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more these immune cells they had.”
At the same time, he suggested that if it turns out that the same applies to humans, then a combination of L. reuteri bacteria and tryptophan-rich diets would help develop a more tolerant and less inflammatory gut environment.
Postgraduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas found that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of the same mice kept separately the cells were missing.
Inferred from the fact that one group of mice has a different intestinal microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that commonly reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The intestines of mice were tested by DNA sequencing, and the researchers found six species of bacteria in mice with immune cells that the second group of mice lacked.
Mice that were bred in a sterile environment and lacked intestinal microbiomes -- they didn't develop this type of immune cell -- were given the L. reuteri bacteria and formed immune cells.
To understand how the bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers cultivated L. reuteri in the fluid and then transferred a small amount of fluid — without the bacteria — to undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
Immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removal of the active ingredient from the liquid, it has been shown to be a by-product of the tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent. After splitting the doses of tryptophan, at the same time, the number of cells decreased by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us retain L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri bacteria cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: “Each of us should probably strive for the development of these cells because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can increase cell population."
