White House props cost taxpayers thousands of dollars.
The White House’s decision to fly a naval helicopter to South Lawn for the celebration of the U.S. manufacturing industry last month came to $24,000, according to naval records released by the weekly TIME.
The Green White Helicopter Sikorsky VH-3D, also known as the Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the culmination of the July 17 White House program, which was a parade of U.S. construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and several senior White House officials watched a show of products from all 50 states.
A Connecticut helicopter was on display next to a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck, and a Mississippi forklift.
A military officer of the White House issued a fragmentary order or FRAGO and requested the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn as part of an "extraordinary" event, the records of the Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) - the helicopters responsible
“I wanted to make sure you were aware of such a significant event,” HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the Navy’s deputy commander for aviation, the day before the event began.
The report suggested that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7:00 a.m. for the occasion of the parade, which is scheduled to begin at 3:00 p.m. and will remain on site until the complete clearing of the entire site, which was scheduled between 6:00 p.m. and 9:00 p.m.
The e-mail further stated that if there is a delay in leaving the White House, a replacement crew will be sent for the return flight due to working time regulations.
The original crew remained on site that evening, along with the helicopter and the security personnel.
From the records - obtained by the weekly magazine TIME - it was not apparent whether the second crew was eventually sent.
The Hatch Act prohibits government officials from using government assets for political purposes.
The records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating possible infringements of this Regulation.
"We were wondering if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was in order," the commander wrote.
'It sounds like you're being blocked, 'said the deputy commander.
This “Made in America” show was designated by the White House as an official event, so the Hatch Act would not apply to it.
But even the official events have political subtexts.
While attending the event, the president advocated a health reform that was passed by the Senate and talked about trying to keep the government regulation under control.
The use of air vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when traveling.
However, their presence purely for presentational reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after the presidential plane flew in the background at his first meeting as part of the campaign in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is overwhelmed with complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessors.
“The White House is delighted with the ‘Made in America’ show, which showcased products from all 50 states that Americans make from American materials,” said Lindsay Walters, a spokeswoman for the White House.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often train landings in the Washington area and on the South Lawn and practice any arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump took part in the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 practice landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America parade was part of the current crew training, the official said.
On the same day, the helicopters flew within the framework of “non-presidential support missions” for another eleven hours.
The White House said no additional requisites were paid from taxpayers’ money.
Sikorsky said the company was not in any way interested in negotiations to expose the helicopter to South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep records of the budget for presidential flights, and the exact cost of the parade is difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly price for fiscal year 2017, reimbursement of DoD expenses for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit records time 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico, Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below the stated amount.
“Indicating the costs of taxpayers on the basis of estimates for reimbursement of expenses is very misleading,” Walters said.
“These estimates include personnel, maintenance, and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual costs.”
According to the 2015 RAND study, DoD reimbursements do not include staff costs, but include fuel prices, maintenance and contract costs.
At the time, White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of helicopters for the purpose of the parade.
"The idea of the show taking place this week is to introduce products made in the U.S.," Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud to contribute to the defense of our state and to provide work for hundreds, if not thousands of people.
I think, like most Americans, we are proud of the helicopter and other military facilities that countless American citizens are involved in.
This fact is to be remembered.”
It is not clear if Trump was also looking at the helicopter during his visit to South Lawn. With certainty, it can only be said that he was behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back in the White House, Trump addressed a Sikorsky representative and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the President, "I own three myself."
